problem:
When moist air comes in contact with a cold surface in the winter, one result can be frost. What has happened to the water vapor in the air to cause frost?
Choices:
  A: It has melted.
  B: It has sublimated.
  C: It has evaporated.
  D: It has condensed.
choices:
Choices:
  A: It has melted.
  B: It has sublimated.
  C: It has evaporated.
  D: It has condensed.
response:
Thought: 
Moist air comes in contact with a cold surface in the winter.
The water vapor in the air changes directly from a gas to a solid, bypassing the liquid phase.
This process is called sublimation.
Action: Answer("B")

problem:
Students are learning about different types of waves. Which is the least likely way for the students to generate a wave?
Choices:
  A: by tossing a ball in the air
  B: by shaking the ends of a rope
  C: by throwing a pebble into a pool of water
  D: by pulling on a coiled spring toy
choices:
Choices:
  A: by tossing a ball in the air
  B: by shaking the ends of a rope
  C: by throwing a pebble into a pool of water
  D: by pulling on a coiled spring toy
response:
Thought: 
Tossing a ball in the air generates a mechanical wave called a transverse wave.
Shaking the ends of a rope generates a mechanical wave called a transverse wave.
Throwing a pebble into a pool of water generates a mechanical wave called a surface wave.
Pulling on a coiled spring toy generates a mechanical wave called a longitudinal wave.
Action: Answer("A")

problem:
A teacher opens a can of food in the front of a classroom. Soon, all of the students in the classroom can smell the food. Which statement identifies a property of a gas that allows all of the students to smell the food?
Choices:
  A: A gas has no mass.
  B: A gas has a large mass.
  C: A gas takes the shape of its container.
  D: A gas keeps its shape when placed in a container.
choices:
Choices:
  A: A gas has no mass.
  B: A gas has a large mass.
  C: A gas takes the shape of its container.
  D: A gas keeps its shape when placed in a container.
response:
Thought: 
The smell of the food is a gas.
Gases take the shape of their container.
The container in this case is the classroom.
The gas spreads throughout the classroom because it takes the shape of the classroom.
Action: Answer("C")

problem:
Sheep Challenge Evolution A species of sheep lives on the Scottish island of Hirta. Hirta has plenty of grass for the sheep to eat, and no natural predators of the sheep live on the island. Some sheep have dark wool, and some have light wool. The sheep with dark wool tend to be much larger and stronger than the sheep with light wool. However, researchers have found that in the last 20 years, the sheep with light wool have increased in number. Usually, strength and size help animals survive and breed. A new sheep predator is introduced to the island. Which change to the sheep population will most likely occur first?
Choices:
  A: a decrease in the population of sheep with dark wool
  B: a decrease in the population of sheep with light wool
  C: an increase in the population of sheep with dark wool
  D: an increase in the population of sheep with light wool
choices:
Choices:
  A: a decrease in the population of sheep with dark wool
  B: a decrease in the population of sheep with light wool
  C: an increase in the population of sheep with dark wool
  D: an increase in the population of sheep with light wool

problem:
The skin is the largest organ in the human body. Why is skin considered to be an organ?
Choices:
  A: It is made of cells.
  B: It acts as a barrier.
  C: It is made of tissues.
  D: It is part of an organism.
choices:
Choices:
  A: It is made of cells.
  B: It acts as a barrier.
  C: It is made of tissues.
  D: It is part of an organism.
response:
Thought: 
An organ is a group of tissues that work together to perform a specific function.
The skin is made up of multiple tissues, including the epidermis, dermis, and subcutaneous layer.
These tissues work together to protect the body from the environment, regulate temperature, and provide sensory information.
Action: Answer("C")

problem:
Margaret is running a full lap around a circular track. She is facing north when she starts. What direction will she be facing after she has completed half of a lap?
Choices:
  A: north
  B: south
  C: east
  D: west
choices:
Choices:
  A: north
  B: south
  C: east
  D: west
response:
Thought: 
Margaret is running a full lap around a circular track. She is facing north when she starts.
After completing half of a lap, she will have traveled 180 degrees around the circle.
Therefore, she will be facing the opposite direction, which is south.
Action: Answer("B")
